INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3700','letter','1780-11-13','','NY','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','How far the sending of the Pennsylvanians towards Aquakanac, and going ourselves to the Hackensac position, may awaken the enemy, I cannot pretend to say.','ltr_laf3700.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3701','letter','1781-03-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Your Excellency remembers that our shortest calculation for the arrival of the troops at the Head of Elk was for the 6th of March. I am happy to inform you that they will be there this day or to-morrow early','ltr_laf3701.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3702','letter','1781-03-07','Head Of Elk River','MD','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Contrary winds, heavy rains, disappointments of vessels, and every inconvenience for which we had no remedy, have been, from the day of my arrival, combined against our embarkation.','ltr_laf3702.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3703','letter','1781-03-15','York','NY','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','On my arrival yesterday afternoon, I found that Baron De Steuben had been very active in making preparations, and, agreeably to what he tells me, we shall have five thousand militia ready to operate.','ltr_laf3703.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3704','letter','1781-03-25','Williamsburg','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','My surprise at not hearing of the French fleet was, I confess, very great, nor could I reconcile my mind to this uncertainty. But intelligence, received yesterday, has put it out of doubt, that they have done their best endeavours towards the cooperation','ltr_laf3704.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3705','letter','1781-04-13','Susquehanna Ferry','','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','By a letter just received from General Greene, I find that he is strongly of opinion that I must go to the southward. His intention is to carry the seat of war into South Carolina','ltr_laf3705.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3706','letter','1781-05-04','Bottoms Creek','','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Every mark of friendship I receive from you adds to my happiness, as I love you with all the sincerity and warmth of my heart; and the sentiment I feel for you goes to the very extent of my affections.','ltr_laf3706.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3707','letter','1781-05-08','Richmond','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','By letters from North Carolina I find that Lord Cornwallis, who, I had been assured, had sailed for Charleston, is advancing towards Halifax.','ltr_laf3707.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3708','letter','1781-05-17','Camp Wilton','','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','The next day the officer returned with the same passport and letter, and informed me that he was now at liberty to declare that Phillips was dead, and Arnold was Commander-in-chief of the British army in Virginia.','ltr_laf3708.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3709','letter','1781-05-24','Richmond','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Public stores and private property being removed from Richmond, this place is a less important object. I do not believe it would be prudent to expose the troops for the sake of a few houses, most of which are empty.','ltr_laf3709.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3710','letter','1781-06-24','Mattapony River','MD','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','My coming into this country has attracted this side a large portion of the enemy\'s force. In the meanwhile General Wayne was filing off towards Westover, and the remainder of the army to Ruffin\'s Ferry. ','ltr_laf3710.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3711','letter','1781-07-20','Malvan Hill','','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','When I went to the southward, you know I had some private objections. But I became sensible of the necessity there was for the detachment to go, and I knew that, had I returned, there was nobody that could lead them','ltr_laf3711.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3712','letter','1781-07-30','Malvan Hill','','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','There are, in Hampton Road, thirty transport ships full of troops, most of them red-coats ; there are eight or ten brigs, which have cavalry on board.','ltr_laf3712.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3713','letter','1781-08-06','Pamunky','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','The embarkation, which I thought and do still think to have been destined to New York, was reported to have sailed up the Bay, and to be bound to Baltimore','ltr_laf3713.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3714','letter','1781-09-30','York','NY','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am far from laughing at the idea of the enemy\'s making a retreat. It is not very probable ; but it is not impossible. Indeed, they have no other way to escape','ltr_laf3714.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3715','letter','1781-10-16','York','NY','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Colonel Gimat\'s battalion led the van, and was followed by that of Colonel Hamilton, who commanded the whole advanced corps. At the same time, a party of eighty men, under Colonel Laurens, turned the redoubt. ','ltr_laf3715.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3716','letter','1781-11-29','','','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Inclosed you will find some numbers, a copy of which I have kept, and which contain some names that may probably occur in our correspondence.','ltr_laf3716.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3717','letter','1781-12-21','Boston','MA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','The moment I arrive in France, I will write to you minutely how things stand, and give you the best accounts in my power.','ltr_laf3717.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3718','letter','1783-02-05','Cadiz','','ESP','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Were you but such a man as Julius Caesar, or the King of Prussia, I should almost be sorry for you at the end of the great tragedy where you are acting such a part. But, with my dear General, I rejoice at the blessings of a peace where our noble ends have been secured.','ltr_laf3718.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3719','letter','1781-09-08','Williamsburg','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Mine of yesterday mentioned that the ships in York River had gone down. Inclosed is an account I receive of an engagement off the Capes.','ltr_laf3719.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3720','letter','1781-04-23','Alexandria','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','When the enemy came to your house, many negroes deserted to them. This piece of news did not affect me much, as I little value those concerns.','ltr_laf3720.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3721','letter','1781-08-21','York River','VA','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','The greater part of the enemy are at York, which they do not as yet fortify ; but are very busy upon Gloucester Neck, where they have a pretty large corps under Colonel Dundas.','ltr_laf3721.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_laf3722','letter','1780-11-28','Paramus','NJ','US','Gilbert du Motier','Lafayette','','George','Washington','','individual','','Unless, however, you were to cast your eye on a man who, I think, would suit better than any other in the world. Hamilton is, I confess, the officer whom I should like to see in that station.','ltr_laf3722.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume III., Jared Sparks, 1853');
